**DL4J** does not include the **OpenCV** native library because the library must be located in the **JAVA_HOME** directory or in an other location where you can precise in your code. If you want to use the features of opencv included in DL4J, you must firstly download the version of opencv included in the version of DL4J you are using.
After downloading the opencv library, The opencv native library is located in
- **opencv/build/java/x64/opencv_javaVERSION_OF_OPENCV.dll** for 64 bits architectures or in
- **opencv/build/java/x86/opencv_javaVERSION_OF_OPENCV.dll** for 32 bits architectures.

 1. You can copy the native library in the java home and do this in your code:
  
   ~~~java
    System.loadLibrary(Core.NATIVE_LIBRARY_NAME);
    Mat imgMat = Imgcodecs.imread(&quot;C:\\Pictures\\image.jpg&quot;);
    INDArray image = loader.asMatrix(imgMat);
   ~~~


2. Or you can use this approach which is the best
~~~java
System.load(&quot;PATH/opencv_javaOPENCV_VERSION.dll&quot;);
Mat imgMat = Imgcodecs.imread(&quot;C:\\Pictures\\image.jpg&quot;);
INDArray image = loader.asMatrix(imgMat);
~~~

**PATH** is the path where to locate the library and **OPENCV_VERSION** is the opencv version you use.

You can adopt the same approach in an other java project based on **opencv**

